[[File:ELISA.jpg|thumb|ELISA: a common immunoassay]]
'''Palaeoimmunology''' or '''paleo-immunology''' ("''paleo''"=ancient, "''immuno''"=referring to [[immunology]]) is the analysis using [[Immunohistochemistry|histochemical]] techniques to look at the [[matrix protein]]s in historic and [[pre-historic]] materials.<ref name=":02" /> Modern [[Immunoassay|immunological assays]] are used to detect the presence of specific [[antigen]]s in the sample material. Specimens subject to immunoassays have usually been preserved in a way that has prevented biomolecular targets from degrading. This has either been achieved through natural preservative circumstances, such as accelerated [[fossil]]ization,<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Schweitzer|first=M. H.|last2=Chiappe|first2=L.|last3=Garrido|first3=A. C.|last4=Lowenstein|first4=J. M.|last5=Pincus|first5=S. H.|year=2005|title=Molecular preservation in Late Cretaceous sauropod dinosaur eggshells|url=http://rspb.royalsocietypublishing.org/content/272/1565/775.short|journal=Proceedings of the Royal Society B|volume=272|issue=1565|via=|doi=10.1098/rspb.2004.2876|pmc=1599869}}</ref> or through artificial [[Mummy|mummification]].<ref name=":02">{{Cite journal|last=Wick|first=Georg|last2=Kalischnig|first2=Gerlinde|last3=Maurer|first3=Herbert|last4=Mayerl|first4=Christina|last5=Muller|first5=Pia Ulrike|year=2001|title=Really old - Palaeoimmunology: Immunohistochemical analysis of extracellular matrix proteins in historic and pre-historic material|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0531556501001413|journal=Experimental Gerontology|volume=36|issue=9|pages=1565–1579|via=|doi=10.1016/s0531-5565(01)00141-3}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|last=Miller|first=R. L.|year=1994|title=Diagnosis of Plasmodium falciparum infections in mummies using the rapid manual ParaSight™-F test|url=http://trstmh.oxfordjournals.org/content/88/1/31.extract#cited-by|journal=Transactions of the Royal Society of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene|volume=88|pages=31–32|via=|doi=10.1016/0035-9203(94)90484-7}}</ref><ref name=":3">{{Cite journal|last=Massa|first=Emma Rabino|last2=Cerutti|first2=Nicoletta|last3=Savoia|first3=A. Martin D.|year=2000|title=Malaria In Ancient Egypt: Paleoimmunological Investigation On Predynastic Mummified Remains|journal=Chungara: Revista de Antropología Chilena|volume=32|pages=7–9|jstor=27802107|via=|doi=10.4067/s0717-73562000000100003}}</ref> Regardless of the path taken to achieve this state, preservation has occurred before the denaturing of antigenic targets.The purpose of applying immunological assays to archaeological materials is to better understand the biochemical makeup and composition of these pre-historic samples.<ref name=":02" /><ref name=":1" /><ref name=":4">{{Cite journal|last=Semal|first=Patrick|last2=Orban|first2=Rosine|year=1995|title=Collagen Extraction from Recent and Fossil Bones: Quantitative and Qualitative Aspects|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0305440385700453|journal=Journal of Archaeological Science|volume=22|issue=4|pages=463–467|via=|doi=10.1006/jasc.1995.0045}}</ref> Antigenic elements within these materials may reveal information regarding the "life" and "death" of the sample being studied.<ref name=":02" /><ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /><ref name=":0" />

== Examples of use ==
Paleo-immunology encompasses a variety of immunoassays performed on a diverse array of archaeological materials. Paleo-immunology is a new, growing field that is still being properly defined. Examples of paleo-immunology as they appear in peer reviewed literature are as follows:
* The extraction and analysis of [[Collagen|collagen peptides]] from fossilized bones.<ref name=":4" /> 
* The use of [[immunofluorescence]] and [[Immunohistochemistry|immunohistochemical]] techniques in order to study the proteins of the [[extracellular matrix]] found in mummified tissues. This was done to further understand the physiologic and pathologic alterations that can occur in preserved prehistoric tissues.<ref name=":02" /> 
* A plague dipstick assay was used to detect the presence of [[Plague (disease)|plague]] antigens in medieval French graves. This paleo-immunological assay is also known as a "rapid diagnostic test for the plague" (RDT).<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Kacki|first=Sacha|last2=Rahalison|first2=Lila|last3=Rajerison|first3=Minoarisoa|last4=Ferroglio|first4=Ezio|last5=Bianucci|first5=Raffaella|year=2011|title=Black Death in the rural cemetery of Saint-Laurent-de-la-Cabrerisse Aude-Languedoc, southern France, 14th century: immunological evidence|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0305440310003675|journal=Journal of Archaeological Science|volume=38|issue=3|pages=581–587|via=|doi=10.1016/j.jas.2010.10.012}}</ref> 
* Enzyme linked immunosorbent assay ([[ELISA]]) was used to detect remnant antigenic structures in preserved [[Sauropoda|sauropod]] eggshells.<ref name=":1" />
* The ParaSight-F test has been used to detect [[malaria]] antigens in Egyptian [[Ancient Egyptian funerary practices|mummies]].<ref name=":2" /><ref name=":3" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Shiff|first=C. J.|last2=Premji|first2=Z.|last3=Minjas|first3=J. N.|year=1993|title=The rapid manual ParaSight®-F test. A new diagnostic tool for Plasmodium falciparum infection|url=http://trstmh.oxfordjournals.org/content/87/6/646|journal=Transactions of the Royal Society of Tropical Medicine and Hygiene|volume=87|issue=6|pages=646–648|via=|doi=10.1016/0035-9203(93)90273-s}}</ref>

